@node encode "DWaRFx À DWaRFx Encode"

@{b}Encryption@{ub} - Lots of options, fairly complex...

 This command is used to send Encrypted messages over irc, so that only
 people with an encoded message decoder can read them.

 Usage: /DwX [$MODE] [!KEY] [DESTINATION] message

   [$MODE] makes the encryptor use one of the following methods:
           $0-$9 = MCF (Using Encryption Table 0-9)
           $A    = Cybeonix (Default)
           $B    = SoundLeech
           $C    = DWaRFx (Uses [!KEY] to encrypt text, if [!KEY] isn't
                   Supplied, the channel name will be used instead)

   [!KEY] is used with the [$MODE] $C (any ascii text, except space)

   [DESTINATION] can output the message as one of the following:

    #[CHANNEL]  = sends the message to the channel (Default)
    *TOPIC      = sets the current channels topic to the message
    /[NICK]     = sends a private message to [NICK]

 Encode Examples:


 /DwX Testing 1.2.3

 This will output the encoded version of 'Testing 1.2.3' to the current
channel, using the default message encryption routine, which is Cybeonix.


 /DwX /COolWAve Testing 1.2.3

 This will output the encoded version of 'Testing 1.2.3' to the nick
'COolWAve', using the default message encryption routine, which is Cybeonix.


 /DwX $4 Hello Everybody!

 This will output the encoded version of 'Hello Everybody!' to the current
channel, using the MCF table 4 message encryption routine.


 /DwX $7 *TOPIC Hello Everybody!

 This will output the encoded version of 'Hello Everybody!' as the topic
for the current channel, using the MCF table 7 message encryption routine.


 /DwX $B #AmIRC The Amiga IRC Channel!

 This will output the encoded version of 'The Amiga IRC Channel!' to the
channel '#AmIRC', using the SoundLeech message encryption routine.


 /DwX $C Hello All DWaRFx Users!

 This will output the encoded version of 'Hello All DWaRFx Users!' to
the current channel, using the DWaRFx message encryption routine. NOTE:
As there is no '!' key used, the message is encoded using the channel
name, and everybody running DWaRFx should be able to read this message!


 /DwX $C !Muppets *TOPIC Hi DWaRFx Users with the key Muppets!

 This will output the encoded version of 'Hi DWaRFx Users with the key
Muppets!' as the topic for the current channel, using the DWaRFx message
encryption routine. NOTE: There is a '!' key used, so the message will
be encoded using the key 'Muppets' (which is case sensitive, which means
that Muppets is not the same as MUPPETS). This means that only people
with their DWaRFx config decode key ('$KEY') set as Muppets will be able
to read this message.

@endnode

@node xdcc "DWaRFx À Xdcc Commands"

XDCC COMMANDS
-------------


The following is a list of commands for XDCC pack control:

/DwXTEST                    - Will show your current XDCC list to you ONLY.
/DwXSHOW <Channel>          - Will show your XDCC list on <Channel>.
/DwXREPEAT <Channel> <Wait> - Same as DwXSHOW, but repeats every <Wait> mins.
/DwXSTOP                    - Stops ALL repeating XDCC lists.
/DwXABORT <Nick>            - Will abort all waiting XDCC sends to <Nick>.

With /DwXSHOW and /DwXREPEAT you can add SHORT as the last parameter, and
this causes DWaRFx to output only a couple of lines, to inform users that
you have files on offer, and for them to ask for a list (this is less likely
to bother users, if you use the /DwXREPEAT command a lot!).



The following is a list of commands for XDCC requesting:

/XLIST <Nick>               - Will request list of packs offered by <Nick>.
/XSEND <Nick> <Pack>        - Will request pack number <Pack> from <Nick>.
/XHELP <Nick>               - Will request list of XDCC commands from <Nick>.


More information on DWaRFx Xdcc...



DWaRFx-TNG XDCC
---------------

XDCC Is a useful part of the IRC experience, if you find you are always
sending and recieving files over IRC. DWaRFx will display a list of files
on offer to selected channels, so users can see what 'Packs' your offering
and request them. 'Packs' are either single files, or groups of files, that
are of a similar type, or for a program with extra files. This save you
having to send file after file, to different users, and only 1 command
is required to get all the files of that pack. This saves time, and IRC
bandwidth, which is always a good thing :).



XDCC PACKS

All the packs are stored in a single text file, called 'XDCC-PACKS' and this
file is located in the DWaRFx directory (Which should be in AmIRC:Rexx/).
This file is just a text file, describing XDCC packs. Any line beggining
with ; is a statement line, and will be ignored (this is just for comments).
Each pack is stored on a seperate line, using space to seperate the fields
of the pack, and # as the start of the next field. The fields of the pack
(which hold information on this pack) are defined in the following format:

#<PACK> #<RATING> #<STATUS> #<PACKNAME> #DESCRIPTION #<FILE-1> [#FILE-X]

<PACK> represents the pack number to be used for this pack. Any valid number
should be put here. This is the number the users will use to request this
pack.

<RATING> represents the quailty value of the pack, and should always be
in the range of 1 to 5, with 1 being poor, and 5 being excellent.

<STATUS> represents the current status of the pack. Which must be one of
the following:

   0 - means this pack is normal
   1 - means this pack is hidden  (only friends can see it, or request it)
   2 - means this pack is not available

<PACKNAME> is the name that will be displayed for this pack.

<DESCRIPTION> is a short description of the file, or files in the pack.

<FILE-1> is the file for this pack. If there are more files, simple add
another #<FILE-X> field to this pack (ie, #<FILE-1> #<FILE-2> #<FILE-3>).

@endnode
@node problems "DWaRFx À FAQ's and problems.."

 DWaRFx Problems - Still can't get DWaRFx working right? Read these babies...
 ---------------

 Note, if your problem is not here, eMail gazy@globalnet.co.uk and I'll answer it.
 Or Join SpryNet.Us.Galaxynet.Org #AmIRC and ask me, my nick's "Gaz".

 Argh! with the release of AmIRC 2.0 and the unexpected XDCC and extra sound 
 features there are sometimes some problems. Mainly swapped Alias's and double
 repsonses from both DWaRFx and AmIRC, not to worry though they aren't fatal,
 just a tad annoying because sometimes you can think its DWaRFx responding, when 
 it isnt. DWaRFx tends to have DWaRFx in its responses etc..
 

 Problem :-

 - No commands are recognised and DWaRFx wont run automatically when I load AmIRC!

 Solutions :-

 - type /Rx Rexx/DWaRFx/DWaRFALIAS.AMIRX and the alias's should be installed. Save
   these as defaults. If this still doesnt work try the next solution :-

 - goto settings>Lists>Alias in your AmIRC. If there are no alias's there then add
   this:-  Murfin = Gareth. Now save these as defaults and re-install DWaRFx. It
   should now work.

 - However, if there are alias's there then check for a file called 'connected.amirx'
   in your AmIRC directory. If it isnt there then copy if from the DWaRFx Directory.
   If it is there then check to see if it is the special 'DWaRFx AND Kuang' one. If
   it is the correct one it should say 'DWaRFx & Kuang Innitiation file' at the top.
   It it doesnt say this then copy it from the DWaRFx Archive.

 - Still Not working? then try looking in your AmIRC for a directory called DWaRFx.
   If it is not there then you should try to re-install DWaRFx.

 - If it's still not working and you need help then join SpryNet.Us.GalaxyNet.Org
   #AmIRC and look for "Gaz", he can help you, thats me ;-)



 Problem :-

 - Argh, whatever I type doesnt seem to work, why are the Syntax's so hard???

 Solution :-

 - Unfortunately DWaRFx has so many commands they are hard to remember. The only
   way to learn them is to keep using it. But I suggest you type /DwHELP or /Dw?
   because it will bring up a list of commands.


 Problem :-

 - DWaRFx is getting me banned because its making me greet & kick and things like
   that!

 Solution :-

 - Type /DwGUI and edit the preferences so that there are no Greet Channels or
   Swearword channels!

 Problem :-

 - The GUI wont load!..

 Solution :-

 - Hmm, it should do. Try double clicking on it manually in the AmIRC/Rexx/DWaRFx
   directory.

 Problem :-

 - Some commands seem to be missing, and others work!

 Solution :-

 - Check and see if its the 'REAL' DWaRFx, the real one is on my homepage at -

   http://www.users.globalnet.co.uk/~gazy/alpha/

   if it was from AmiNet than it will be missing a few files!

 Problem :-

 - DWaRFx crashes with sound requests!!!?!?

 Solution :-

 - This is an AmIRC problem! Get an earlier AmIRC or Turn off DWaRFx's sounds and
   use AmIRC for sounds.

 Problems :-

 - The flood protection doesn't work!

 Solution :-

 - yes it has been removed :-( expect an update soon.

 Problem :-

 - The GUI wont come up!

 Solution :-

 - Dodgy.. try wearing a pink dressing gown and parading around with 'j0nka' tatooed
   on your bottom.

@endnode
